point to discuss larger issues of Black Power, the end of empire, British race relations, immigration, and student rights. Coinciding with a student-led campaign against segregated housing, the visit enabled Malcolm X to make connections with radical students from the Caribbean, Africa, and South Asia, giving him a new perspective on the global struggle for racial equality, and in turn, radicalizing a new generation of British activists. Masterfully tracing the reverberations on both sides of the Atlantic, Tuck chronicles how the personal transformation of the dynamic American leader played out on the international stage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAfrican AmericansxCivil rights. 0aAnti-racismxHistoryx20th centuryxEnglandxOxfordxEnglandxOxford. 0aAnti-racismzEnglandzOxfordxHistoryy20th century. 0aBlack Muslims. 0aCivil rights movementsxHistoryx20th century. 0aCivil rights movementsxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh1 aGates, Henry Louis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015z978311062111240uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052095998940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520959989423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520959989/original  a978-3-11-062111-2  University of California Press Complete Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles